    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-09-27T16:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-09-27T16:30:00-05:00" n="157"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <head>157. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d157fn0"
                        >Source: Department of State, Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation: Lot 64
                        D199. Secret; Presidential Handling. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_GJNJ1"
                            >Greene</persName>. The meeting was held at the Sheraton Plaza
                        Hotel.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <gloss target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>–9</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Boston</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1958-09-27T17:30:00-04:00"
                            >September 27, 1958, 5:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">SECRETARY’s TRIP TO BOSTON</p>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">United States</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>The Secretary</item>
                            <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BWR1">Burgess</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GJNJ1">Greene</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName>Compton</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">
                            <hi rend="italic">NATO</hi>
                        </gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Secretary General <persName corresp="#p_SPH1">Paul Henri
                                    Spaak</persName>
                                <note n="1" xml:id="d157fn1">
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SPH1">Spaak</persName> paid an unofficial
                                    visit to the United States September 26–28. He and Secretary
                                        <persName>Dulles</persName> were in Boston to address the
                                    Atlantic Treaty Association on September 27. For texts of their
                                    speeches, see Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                                        >Bulletin,</hi> October 13, 1958, pp. 571–574, and October
                                    20, 1958, pp. 607–611.</note>
                            </item>
                            <item>M. St. M’leux</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_DGC1">De Gaulle</persName>’s views on <gloss
                            target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>M. <persName corresp="#p_SPH1">Spaak</persName> told the Secretary that General
                        <persName corresp="#p_DGC1">De Gaulle</persName> had given him a copy of the
                    memorandum which the General had sent to President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> and Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Macmillan</persName> on September 17.<note n="2" xml:id="d157fn2">Part 2,
                            <ref target="#d45">Document 45</ref>.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SPH1">M. Spaak</persName> expressed his concern that if
                        <persName corresp="#p_DGC1">De Gaulle</persName> presses his proposal it
                    will be the end of <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>. The Italians and
                    Germans would not tolerate it. <persName corresp="#p_SPH1">M. Spaak</persName>
                    thought it important to raise for discussion some of the issues General
                        <persName corresp="#p_DGC1">De Gaulle</persName> presented but he heartily
                    disagreed with the idea of trying to revise the North Atlantic Treaty. Also he
                    wholly disapproved of the idea in the <persName corresp="#p_DGC1">De
                        Gaulle</persName> memorandum of injecting the military standing group into
                    what should be political consultations—if any.</p>
                <p>The Secretary said he had found in general one good element and one bad in the
                        <persName corresp="#p_DGC1">De Gaulle</persName> memorandum. Since it is a
                    fact that the ability of the United Nations to deal with serious issues is
                    deteriorating with the proliferation of membership, it is legitimate for the
                    members of <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> to consider how best they may
                    deal with such issues, on a global basis. Consultation within <gloss
                        target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>, of the sort which <persName
                        corresp="#p_SPH1">M. Spaak</persName> had just been discussing, and the
                    contacts which <persName corresp="#p_SPH1">M. Spaak</persName> had initiated
                    with his counterparts in other regional organizations, might be viewed in this
                    context. But the idea of a “world directorate” comprising the United States,
                    Britain and France is wholly unacceptable to the United States.</p>
                <pb facs="0396" n="360" xml:id="pg_360"/>
                <p>M. <persName corresp="#p_SPH1">Spaak</persName> shared these views.</p>
                <p>The Secretary noted that he had told Ambassador Alphand and <persName
                        corresp="#p_CMM1">Couve de Murville</persName>, as well as <persName
                        corresp="#p_LS1">Selwyn Lloyd</persName>,<note n="3" xml:id="d157fn3">A
                        memorandum of <persName>Dulles</persName>’ conversation with <persName
                            corresp="#p_CMM1">Couve de Murville</persName> and Alphand is printed in
                        Part 2 as <ref target="#d46">Document 46</ref>. On September 26 at 11 a.m.,
                            <persName>Dulles</persName> met with <persName corresp="#p_LS1"
                            >Lloyd</persName>, informed him of the contents of <persName
                            corresp="#p_DGC1">De Gaulle</persName>’s letter, and told him the United
                        States wanted to consult with the United Kingdom about a reply. He asked
                            <persName corresp="#p_LS1">Lloyd</persName> to send him the British
                        views after speaking to <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Macmillan</persName>.
                        (Department of State, Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation: Lot 64 D
                        199)</note> that <persName corresp="#p_DGC1">De Gaulle</persName>’s
                    memorandum raised serious issues which would have to be carefully studied in the
                    United States Government. The Secretary said that he thought this study would
                    take quite some time.</p>
            </div>
